  "local_port": 39536,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do I make Pani puri chutney in Tamil Nadu style?",
  "response": "Pani Puri, also known as Golgappa or Puchka in different regions of India, is a popular street food that comes with flavorful water (pani) and chutneys. The Tamil Nadu style pani puri chutney often includes a combination of herbs and spices that gives it a distinct taste. Here\u2019s a simple recipe to make the chutney in the Tamil Nadu style:\n\n### Ingredients\n\n#### For Pani (Spicy Water)\n- 1 cup fresh mint leaves\n- 1 cup fresh coriander leaves (cilantro)\n- 2-3 green chilies (adjust to taste)\n- 1-inch piece of ginger\n- 1-2 tablespoons tamarind paste (or to taste)\n- 1 teaspoon roasted cumin powder\n- 1 teaspoon chaat masala (optional)\n- Salt to taste\n- Water (as needed)\n- Lemon juice (optional, to taste)\n\n#### For the Sweet Chutney\n- 1 cup tamarind juice\n- 1/2 cup jaggery, grated (or brown sugar as a substitute)\n- 1/2 teaspoon roasted cumin powder\n- 1/4 teaspoon red chili powder (optional)\n- Salt to taste\n\n### Instructions\n\n#### For the Pani:\n1. **Blend the Herbs**: In a blender, combine mint leaves, coriander leaves, green chilies, ginger, and tamarind paste. Add a little water to help blend into a smooth paste.\n\n2. **Mix the Spices**: Once blended, transfer the mixture to a bowl. Add roasted cumin powder, chaat masala (if using), and salt. Mix well.\n\n3. **Adjust Consistency**: Add more water to reach your desired consistency for the spicy water. Taste and adjust the seasoning if needed. You can also add a little lemon juice for extra tanginess.\n\n4. **Chill**: Refrigerate the pani for at least 30 minutes before serving to allow the flavors to meld.\n\n#### For the Sweet Chutney:\n1. **Prepare Tamarind Juice**: If using tamarind pulp, soak a small ball of it in warm water, then strain to get the juice. \n\n2. **Cook the Chutney**: In a saucepan, add the tamarind juice, grated jaggery, roasted cumin powder, and red chili powder (if using). Heat it over low flame, stirring until the jaggery dissolves completely. Allow it to simmer for a few minutes until it thickens slightly.\n\n3. **Cool and Store**: Once cooked, allow it to cool and store in an airtight container.\n\n### Serving\nTo serve, take puris and fill them with boiled potatoes or chickpeas (or your preferred filling), then dip them into the spicy water and drizzle some sweet chutney over it. Enjoy your Tamil Nadu style Pani Puri!\n\nFeel free to adjust the spices and ingredients according to your preference. Enjoy making and relishing this delicious street food at home!",
